                "lng": -118.2440971,
                "mapUrl": "https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=34.0898739,-118.2440971",
                "description": "A rare and striking example of Mayan Revival architecture applied at a residential scale, designed by the eccentric architect Robert Stacy-Judd. Built in 1931, the bungalow court features bold geometric patterns and stylized moldings drawn from ancient Central American temples \u2014 an exotic aesthetic Stacy-Judd championed as the basis for a genuinely \"American\" architectural style, distinct from European traditions. Unlike grander Mayan Revival statements such as Stacy-Judd's own Aztec Hotel in Monrovia, these bungalows bring the style to an intimate, everyday residential scale, making them one of the rarest surviving examples of this brief but fascinating chapter in Los Angeles architectural history.",
                "original_hood": "Echo Park"
