                "type": "landmark",
                "description": "Once an elite 1920s enclave of Spanish-style mansions favored by Hollywood celebrities like Cecil B. DeMille, Surfridge was slowly consumed by the expansion of LAX and the unbearable noise of jet engines. By the 1970s, all homes had been demolished or relocated. Today it is a 'ghost neighborhood' where paved streets, curbs, and original streetlights remain intact, but no houses stand. The area is now a protected habitat for the El Segundo Blue Butterfly and is strictly off-limits to the public.",
